//Invert Binary Tree
//Given the root of a binary tree, invert the tree, and return its root.
//Example 1:
//Input: root = [4,2,7,1,3,6,9]
//Output: [4,7,2,9,6,3,1]
//Example 2:
//Input: root = [2,1,3]
//Output: [2,3,1]
//Example 3:
//Input: root = []
//Output: []

Brute force approach -> 

class Solution {
public:
    TreeNode* invertTree(TreeNode* root) {
        if(root == nullptr) {
            return nullptr;
        }
        TreeNode* newRoot = new TreeNode(root->val);        
        newRoot->left = invertTree(root->right);
        newRoot->right = invertTree(root->left);
        return newRoot;
    }
};

Note:
We recursively invert the original right and left subtrees, then attach them in opposite positions while building a completely new tree.

Complexity Analysis ->

Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes in the tree
Reason:
Every node is visited once.

Space Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes in the tree
Reason:
A completely new tree is created.

Optimal Approach ->            //[In brute force approach rather than changing the nodes in the tree itself we are creating an entirely new tree which increases memory consumption]

class Solution {
public:
    TreeNode* invertTree(TreeNode* root) {
        if(root == nullptr) {
            return nullptr;
        }
        swap(root->left, root->right);
        invertTree(root->left);
        invertTree(root->right);
        return root;
    }
};

Note:
Here we directly swap the left and right child of every node in the original tree, then recursively invert the remaining subtrees.

Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes in the tree
Reason:
Every node is visited exactly once.

Space Complexity -> O(h)
where:
h = height of the tree
Reason:
Recursive call stack stores at most h function calls at one time.


Corner Cases ->

1. Empty Tree
root = []
Output:
[]

2. Single Node
    1
Output:
    1
(No children to swap.)

3. Only Left Child
    1
   /
  2
Output:
    1
     \
      2

4. Only Right Child
    1
     \
      2
Output:
    1
   /
  2

5. Perfect Binary Tree
        4
      /   \
     2     7
    / \   / \
   1  3  6  9
Output:
        4
      /   \
     7     2
    / \   / \
   9  6  3  1
